01:06:50.709 --> 01:06:51.709
David McWilliams: Okay, you know.
About 15 months ago -- 14 months ago -- I

01:06:51.709 --> 01:06:52.709
had this unusual occurrence, which is in the
book, which again, has detracted from the

01:06:52.709 --> 01:06:53.709
book, because it's where the minister came
to my house to chat about stuff.

01:06:53.709 --> 01:06:54.709
And what had happened was, I had gone on a
radio program with him.

01:06:54.709 --> 01:06:55.709
And I said the banks were going to go bust
in this country and that's our big problem.

01:06:55.709 --> 01:06:56.709
And he said, "Oh, you can't talk like that.
That's dangerous talk."

01:06:56.709 --> 01:06:57.709
Now, I actually felt a lot of sympathy for
him, because if he even talks to the vice

01:06:57.709 --> 01:06:58.709
_____, he couldn't as a minister say that.
But, you know, I was watching his body language

01:06:58.709 --> 01:06:59.709
and the leader of the opposition, a finance
spokesman, and they really believe the banks

01:06:59.709 --> 01:07:00.709
were fine.
So that was in the sixth of September, and

01:07:00.709 --> 01:07:01.709
I kept writing that the banks would be in
trouble -- not because I knew anything about

01:07:01.709 --> 01:07:02.709
what was going on in the banks, but because
I knew about economics and cycles and what

01:07:02.709 --> 01:07:03.709
happens, right?
And I'd seen it -- I'd seen it in Argentina,

01:07:03.709 --> 01:07:04.709
I'd seen it in Serbia, I'd seen in Israel
 -- all these places.

01:07:04.709 --> 01:07:05.709
I worked in Russia -- same carry on, right?
And then the other day, I went on prime time,

01:07:05.709 --> 01:07:06.709
and again, the same thing.
Government spokespeople coming out -- central

01:07:06.709 --> 01:07:07.709
bankers saying, "The banks are fine."
And I was like, "The dogs in the street know

01:07:07.709 --> 01:07:08.709
they're bust."
We're going to lose all our deposits, because

01:07:08.709 --> 01:07:09.709
these guys have been so cavalier with their
own finance, that they won't give a damn if

01:07:09.709 --> 01:07:10.709
they drag all the deposits with them on a
run on the bank.

01:07:10.709 --> 01:07:11.709
That's I suppose my -- when the minister arrived
in my house, we were discussing this.

01:07:11.709 --> 01:07:12.709
And I thought -- not just me, but some other
people.

01:07:12.709 --> 01:07:13.709
Not lots of other people -- thought that a
full guarantee, which is what the Swedes had

01:07:13.709 --> 01:07:14.709
done in '92, might work.
And the argument was, "Well, what about Anglo?"

01:07:14.709 --> 01:07:15.709
Even back then, if you guarantee Anglo, are
you not guaranteeing something that you can't

01:07:15.709 --> 01:07:16.709
unravel?
And my argument was at the time -- and it's

01:07:16.709 --> 01:07:17.709
still in the book, and it's still what I make
was, the guarantee prevented a run on our

01:07:17.709 --> 01:07:18.709
banks.
And it was incredibly successful as a policy.

01:07:18.709 --> 01:07:19.709
It now runs out on the first of October of
next year, 28th of September of next year.

01:07:19.709 --> 01:07:20.709
So what we should be doing now, with the likes
of Anglo, okay? is saying to the creditors

01:07:20.709 --> 01:07:21.709
of Anglo, "Those of you lucky enough to have
very short-term paper with Anglo covered by

01:07:21.709 --> 01:07:22.709
the guarantee, we'll pay you."
But that's a fraction of the total Anglo liability

01:07:22.709 --> 01:07:23.709
with creditors.
"The rest of you, we can give you a hundred

01:07:23.709 --> 01:07:24.709
percent today" -- or we're not going to give
you that, because you know that the markets

01:07:24.709 --> 01:07:25.709
are liquid -- "But if you wait, at this time
next year, you'll get zero, because the banks

01:07:25.709 --> 01:07:26.709
are closing." Now what do you want to do?
You should start negotiating with the creditors

01:07:26.709 --> 01:07:27.709
under the terms of the guarantee.
Because they are stuck.

01:07:27.709 --> 01:07:28.709
And I come back to the guys in London who
can't believe that we, as a nation, are going

01:07:28.709 --> 01:07:29.709
to spend 28 billion of NAMA money on Anglo,
which is a basket case.

01:07:29.709 --> 01:07:30.709
So we've got to go back first, use the guarantee,
so that my mother and your deposits don't

01:07:30.709 --> 01:07:31.709
fly out, so you don't have a run on the bank.
Then negotiate with the creditors.

01:07:31.709 --> 01:07:32.709
And what you should do with something like
Anglo is, go to someone like AIB and say,

01:07:32.709 --> 01:07:33.709
"Do you want the deposit book of Anglo?" because
there is a deposit book there.

01:07:33.709 --> 01:07:34.709
Sell that a little bit off, and then do what
you do when the Swede shop went bust.

01:07:34.709 --> 01:07:35.709
You know, you deal with everyone.
Creditors take ten cents on the dollar, and

